  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in the United States and in many other jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This typically involves three stages: placement, layering, and integration.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prosecuted under several federal statutes, including the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA), the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986, and the USA PATRIOT Act. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines and imprisonment. For example, under U.S. federal law, a conviction for money laundering can result in a prison sentence of up to 20 years and fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n\nAdditionally, money laundering can lead to charges under other related statutes, such as those related to fraud, conspiracy, or racketeering, which can further increase the severity of the penalties.\n\nIt's important to note that the specifics of money laundering laws and penalties can vary by jurisdiction, but it is universally treated as a serious criminal offense.",
